ed to inspect the README of the source, though it doesn’t seem necessary right now. I think the specification should mention the public interfaces, especially as I plan the file/module layout for the new architecture. Since the user asked about the \\\"multicodex-core + pi adapter boundaries,\\\" I’ll likely need to propose new files and package roots. I should create a map from the current index.ts to the new modules, considering the current monolithic structure. It might be helpful to draft a detailed specification based on the target state, incorporating core library and adapter files.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Deciding on documentation structure**\\n\\nThe spec contract indicates that detailed content should live under spec/, so I should probably create at least one detailed document along with a spec.md index. However, the user only mentioned spec.md specifically. I’m leaning towards creating a single detailed spec.md if that’s all they requested, but it might be more aligned with the contract to include detail docs. Considering the instruction hierarchy, I think I can include everything in spec.md while keeping it well-structured without needing additional files, unless really necessary.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying documentation requirements**\\n\\nI’m considering that even though “keep concise” is mentioned, the user specifically asked for a detailed spec, so it makes sense to write all sections in one file. I’ll include top-level headings and subheadings to keep it organized. Since I have to ensure not to modify source code, I’ll focus solely on creating the spec.md. It looks like I’m working within the permitted scope under .agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic despite any other instructions regarding AGENTS.md.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating task specifications**\\n\\nThe user requests to create a specification in the repo under `.agents/tasks/...`, which seems outside usual guidelines. The developer mentions project-specific instructions from AGENTS.md, which feels odd. However, since this task is within the kg-multicodex repo, it might be acceptable. I’ll need to inspect the current files in `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/context/restructure...` and also look at `index.test.ts` to understand any gaps. Listing helper function names from the monolith will be helpful too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Mapping line numbers**\\n\\nI'm considering getting line numbers or regions that could be useful for mapping purposes. Reading with offsets might make this easier. I need to identify the line numbers for sections in `index.ts` to properly map the modules. Using grep to search for `// =============================================================================` and function names seems like a good approach. This should help me create a clear mapping that aligns with the code structure. I'll make sure to stay organized while doing this!\"}]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_z3WPuI3omqsiGEG3cNB5CY9W|fc_0ad2abd70cca7d330169de0147fdc88199955ab9541cc7b534","name":"grep","arguments":{},"partialJson":""}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4-mini","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776156974155,"responseId":"resp_0ad2abd70cca7d330169de012eebf881999b11e7ebc915ac0a"}}
{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_end","contentIndex":1,"toolCall":{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_z3WPuI3omqsiGEG3cNB5CY9W|fc_0ad2abd70cca7d330169de0147fdc88199955ab9541cc7b534","name":"grep","arguments":{"path":"/home/linkdevk/repos/kg-multicodex/index.ts","pattern":"^// =============================================================================","limit":50}},"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Evaluating repo refactoring**\n\nI'm considering whether the reference pertains to the current repository before simplification. It seems there's a goal to create a platform-agnostic core based on the existing codebase. Since the current repo is a monolith with tests around the core, I'd need a specification for transforming it into a core + adapter structure. I might consider the source implementation to guide boundaries and behaviors. Also, ensuring behavior parity by referencing existing tests and documentation seems crucial. I'll need to check the current package files for any discrepancies as well.\n\n**Investigating package.json issues**\n\nI noticed that while listing files in the repo root, package.json didn’t appear, which is puzzling since earlier, reading the root package.json was successful. Maybe it’s missing, or the listing command has limitations? I found package-lock.json and Makefile, but not package.json. It seems odd that the read succeeded, suggesting it existed then. Perhaps the listing command uses .gitignore rules, but that seems unlikely. I might need to check the .agents/sources/pi-multicodex for module names, which I've already done.\n\n**Planning the new architecture**\n\nI’m considering whether I need to inspect the README of the source, though it doesn’t seem necessary right now. I think the specification should mention the public interfaces, especially as I plan the file/module layout for the new architecture. Since the user asked about the \"multicodex-core + pi adapter boundaries,\" I’ll likely need to propose new files and package roots. I should create a map from the current index.ts to the new modules, considering the current monolithic structure. It might be helpful to draft a detailed specification based on the target state, incorporating core library and adapter files.\n\n**Deciding on documentation structure**\n\nThe spec contract indicates that detailed content should live under spec/, so I should probably create at least one detailed document along with a spec.md index. However, the user only mentioned spec.md specifically. I’m leaning towards creating a single detailed spec.md if that’s all they requested, but it might be more aligned with the contract to include detail docs. Considering the instruction hierarchy, I think I can include everything in spec.md while keeping it well-structured without needing additional files, unless really necessary.\n\n**Clarifying documentation requirements**\n\nI’m considering that even though “keep concise” is mentioned, the user specifically asked for a detailed spec, so it makes sense to write all sections in one file. I’ll include top-level headings and subheadings to keep it organized. Since I have to ensure not to modify source code, I’ll focus solely on creating the spec.md. It looks like I’m working within the permitted scope under .agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic despite any other instructions regarding AGENTS.md.\n\n**Evaluating task specifications**\n\nThe user requests to create a specification in the repo under `.agents/tasks/...`, which seems outside usual guidelines. The developer mentions project-specific instructions from AGENTS.md, which feels odd. However, since this task is within the kg-multicodex repo, it might be acceptable. I’ll need to inspect the current files in `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/context/restructure...` and also look at `index.test.ts` to understand any gaps. Listing helper function names from the monolith will be helpful too.\n\n**Mapping line numbe