son didn’t appear, which is puzzling since earlier, reading the root package.json was successful. Maybe it’s missing, or the listing command has limitations? I found package-lock.json and Makefile, but not package.json. It seems odd that the read succeeded, suggesting it existed then. Perhaps the listing command uses .gitignore rules, but that seems unlikely. I might need to check the .agents/sources/pi-multicodex for module names, which I've already done.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Planning the new architecture**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I need to inspect the README of the source, though it doesn’t seem necessary right now. I think the specification should mention the public interfaces, especially as I plan the file/module layout for the new architecture. Since the user asked about the \\\"multicodex-core + pi adapter boundaries,\\\" I’ll likely need to propose new files and package roots. I should create a map from the current index.ts to the new modules, considering the current monolithic structure. It might be helpful to draft a detailed specification based on the target state, incorporating core library and adapter files.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Deciding on documentation structure**\\n\\nThe spec contract indicates that detailed content should live under spec/, so I should probably create at least one detailed document along with a spec.md index. However, the user only mentioned spec.md specifically. I’m leaning towards creating a single detailed spec.md if that’s all they requested, but it might be more aligned with the contract to include detail docs. Considering the instruction hierarchy, I think I can include everything in spec.md while keeping it well-structured without needing additional files, unless really necessary.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying documentation requirements**\\n\\nI’m considering that even though “keep concise” is mentioned, the user specifically asked for a detailed spec, so it makes sense to write all sections in one file. I’ll include top-level headings and subheadings to keep it organized. Since I have to ensure not to modify source code, I’ll focus solely on creating the spec.md. It looks like I’m working within the permitted scope under .agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic despite any other instructions regarding AGENTS.md.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating task specifications**\\n\\nThe user requests to create a specification in the repo under `.agents/tasks/...`, which seems outside usual guidelines. The developer mentions project-specific instructions from AGENTS.md, which feels odd. However, since this task is within the kg-multicodex repo, it might be acceptable. I’ll need to inspect the current files in `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/context/restructure...` and also look at `index.test.ts` to understand any gaps. Listing helper function names from the monolith will be helpful too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Mapping line numbers**\\n\\nI'm considering getting line numbers or regions that could be useful for mapping purposes. Reading with offsets might make this easier. I need to identify the line numbers for sections in `index.ts` to properly map the modules. Using grep to search for `// =============================================================================` and function names seems like a good approach. This should help me create a clear mapping that aligns with the code structure. I'll make sure to stay organized while doing this!\"}]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_z3WPuI3omqsiGEG3cNB5CY9W|fc_0ad2abd70cca7d330169de0147fdc88199955ab9541cc7b534","name":"grep","arguments":{"path":"/home/linkdevk/repos/kg-multicodex/index.ts","pattern":"^// =============================================================================","limit":50},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/home/linkdevk/repos/kg-multicodex/index.ts\",\"pattern\":\"^// ====================================================================