t changing the `pi` package entrypoint path or existing export names initially for consistency. I'd mention that tests should be moved, but keeping the root `index.test.ts` for smoke testing during the migration makes sense. I aim to draft a spec that’s detailed but concise, around 1000-1500 words. I need to decide if the spec should address the `multicodex-core` package boundary without introducing an npm workspace commitment.\n\n**Defining implementation conventions**\n\nI’m thinking about defining some implementation conventions. I might say that `core/*` represents the platform-agnostic boundary, while `pi/*` indicates the adapter boundary. If we later decide to split packaging into workspaces, these modules will serve as the package roots without needing any API changes. This approach seems solid, and I want to ensure it’s clear for everyone involved. Writing this down will help clarify our structure and expectations moving forward.\n\n**Considering implementation notes**\n\nI'm analyzing the current state of the reference implementation, which already divides along specific seams that should guide module ownership. There are some intentional behavior differences to preserve, like manual selection, an untouched-first heuristic, and current command aliases. I should note the `agent` memory about these behavior seams instead of focusing on arbitrary file size splits. Integrating with the module extraction map based on behavior seams could be beneficial. Should I include line numbers as well?\n\n**Structuring the spec document**\n\nI’m considering how to best structure the spec document without linking to other documents. Since the task specifies writing the output in `spec.md`, it seems fine to keep everything in one file. I should probably create a final spec with sections and maybe tables. I think we can limit ourselves to about 8-10 major headings and use concise yet detailed bullet points. No code modifications are necessary; I’m ready to write!","thinkingSig